{"title":"Classic UK climb: Rest and Be Thankful","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/rest-and-be-thankful-cycling","date":1780330848000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/rest-and-be-thankful-cycling\">Classic UK climb: Rest and Be Thankful</a></p>\n\n<p>We cyclists might assume we hold a monopoly on hill climbs. However back in 1906 – around 40 years before the first British Hill Climb Championship on two wheels – the first edition of the motorists’ Rest and Be Thankful Speed Hill Climb was held in the West Highlands.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The country’s best drivers were invited to tackle a 1.3km section of the Old Military Road that now sits alongside the A83 between Loch Lomond and Loch Fyne. Big names on the British motor racing scene would make the trip to the Highland race, including none other than Jackie Stewart, the Scottish three-time winner of the Formula 1 Driver’s Championship, and his countryman and hero Jim Clark, another two-time F1 World Champion. It’s the equivalent of Tadej Pogačar and Jonas Vingegaard dropping by to race in your local town centre criterium.</p>\n\n\n\n<div></div>\n\n\n\n<p>If BBC Radio 2’s <em>Drivetime</em> is more your speed, however, you might have heard the unusually named Rest and Be Thankful pop up in the traffic report. The pass’s frequent landslides wreak havoc in the region, cutting off this crucial pinch point between the West Highlands and Central Belt.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Being the Highlands’ answer to Spaghetti Junction means that there are several ways to ride up Rest and Be Thankful. You could opt for the Military Road, used by the motoring speedsters of old; the mudslide-prone A83; or you can get there via a long ascent through Glen Mhor, which measures 4.3km in length at an average gradient of 6%. With slopes persistently over 10% in its stinging second half, the Glen Mhor route is the most challenging way to make the journey to the 300m summit, which is why it’s the one we’ve featured here.</p>\n\n\n\n<p><a href=\"#h-the-rest-is-history\"><img src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/02/classic-climb-roundel-attempt-e1772020114570.webp\" alt=\"\" /></a><em><strong><mark><a href=\"#h-the-rest-is-history\">Article continues below…</a></mark></strong></em></p>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-2.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>This route through Glen Mhor is the toughest of several climbs that end at the Rest and Be Thankful.</figcaption><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-3.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>The road is narrow but well surfaced.</figcaption><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-4.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-5.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-6.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>Towards the end of the climb is where it gets steepest as the road goes through a series of S-bends.</figcaption><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-7.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-8.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>The stone instructing travellers to rest and be thankful has stood in the pass since the 18th century.</figcaption><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-970x647.webp\" alt=\"Rest and Be Thankful\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-970x646.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-300x200.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-768x513.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-750x500.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-1140x761.webp 1140w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-465x310.webp 465w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-620x413.webp 620w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9-350x233.webp 350w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/06/rest-and-be-thankful-9.webp 1536w\" /><figcaption>Once over the summit of the climb, there is another kilometre of easy riding to go before you arrive at the Rest and Be Thankful.</figcaption><figcaption>Jeremy Sutton-Hibbert</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<h2>The rest is history</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The Glen Mhor route up ‘The Rest’ starts about halfway along the B839 that runs between Loch Goil and Loch Long. A junction signposted towards Glasgow marks the base of the climb, with the gradients immediately tilting up to 5% before seesawing intermittently for the first half-kilometre.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This early section is narrow, requiring passing places for cars, but the tarmac is freshly laid, smooth and sheltered by a canopy of protruding pines. To the side, the ground drops away sharply down to the River Goil, named after the nearby loch it flows into. The river, or burn as they say in this neck of the woods, follows the road as it makes a gentle kilometre-long curve, never rising above 6% in gradient during this stretch.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>From here, roughly 2km into the climb, the road points dead straight towards Beinn an Lochain, a 901m hill that falls just over 10m short of qualifying as one of Scotland’s famed Munros. More than half the mountain is coated in bruised shades of brown and green, the same colour palette that dominates the bracken and gorse on either side of the progressively steepening road.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>With just under half the climb left to tackle, the gradient ratchets up to 8% and 9% stretches, with the result that the road feels the need to throw in a set of S-bends that are not quite sharp enough to be labelled hairpins. It’s during these shimmies in the road that you reach the toughest pitch, a 16% ramp that comes just before the road eases up for a gentle final stretch. As the road tapers slightly, the views into Glen Croe become more impressive by the metre, with the Arrochar Alps in full splendour, each peak towering well above 800m.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>When the summit arrives after 4.3km in the saddle, the vista opens up spectacularly, but this is not the Rest and Be Thankful. That actually lies another kilometre further on after a gentle downhill run. From your high point, you’ll be able to spot the Old Military Road, the track of the old Hill Climb, wiggling up the glen through the expanse of highland scrub to meet the junction of the Rest and Be Thankful in the distance.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>The poet John Keats once described The Rest as a ‘tremendous glen with nothing but a stone’. That memorial stone, found just a short detour from the end of the ride, has stood within the Glen Croe since the mid-18th century, carved with the phrase ‘Rest and Be Thankful’. This cereal box-sized piece of masonry is precisely where the climb’s name comes from, and it was erected for the soldiers who slogged their way through the glen just after the final Jacobite Uprising.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>And while there are no bayonet-wielding monarchists to flee from these days, the message still rings true, especially after a good 20 minutes stamping on the pedals.</p>\n\n\n<div>\n<figure><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/newsletters\" target=\"_blank\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"970\" height=\"250\" src=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-970x250.webp\" alt=\"\" srcset=\"https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-970x250.webp 970w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-300x77.webp 300w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-768x198.webp 768w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-1536x396.webp 1536w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-2048x528.webp 2048w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-750x193.webp 750w, https://cdn-jupiter.metropolis.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2026/03/Newsletter-flash-v3-3-1140x294.webp 1140w\" /></a><figcaption></figcaption></figure></div>\n\n\n<h2>The stats</h2>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Location</strong> Lochgoilhead, Argyll<br /><strong>Length</strong> 4.3km<br /><strong>Summit height </strong>295m<br /><strong>Ascent</strong> 253m<br /><strong>Average gradient</strong> 6%<br /><strong>Maximum gradient </strong>16%<br /><strong>Current best Strava time (to Glen Mhor summit)<br />KoM</strong> Ross Fawcett, UK, 10min 17sec<br /><strong>QoM</strong> Hannah Rhodes, UK, 16min 10sec</p>\n<p>The post <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/rest-and-be-thankful-cycling\">Classic UK climb: Rest and Be Thankful</a> appeared first on <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a>.</p>","author":"Mdonlevy","siteTitle":"Cyclist.co.uk","siteHash":"561486e7070fa5351de9318ad0fa26c2a39332acba5fc7c7d1694a01d53d431e","entryHash":"3fcdcba8ec8d042096f417a25192197f8a8683e62d29f4951d9766878a108160","category":"Cycling"}